{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos107.erdos_107 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos107.erdos_107.","id":"vf_8f7856a1290d5b01","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #107 [status: falsifiable; formalized: yes]. Let $f(n)$ be minimal such that any $f(n)$ points in $\\mathbb{R}^2$, no three on a line, contain $n$ points which form the vertices of a convex $n$-gon. Prove that $f(n)=2^{n-2}+1$. Current best: Erd\\H{o}s and Szekeres proved the bounds\\[2^{n-2}+1\\leq f(n)\\leq \\binom{2n-4}{n-2}+1.\\](\\cite{ErSz60} and \\cite{ErSz35} respectively). There were several improvements of the upper bound, but all of the form $4^{(1+o(1))n}$, until Suk \\cite{Su17} proved\\[f(n) \\leq 2^{(1+o(1))n}.\\]The current best bound is due to Holmsen, Mojarrad, Pach, and Tardos \\cite{HMPT20}, who prove\\[f(n) \\leq 2^{n+O(\\sqrt{n\\log n})}.\\]In \\cite{Er97e} Erd\\H{o}s clarifies that the \\$500 is for a proof, and only offers \\$100 for a disproof. Prize: $500. OEIS: A000051. Tags: convex, geometry.","id":"vf_a9097288c26b9cb0","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"claim":"Pinned authored activity; it does not establish mathematical truth.","id":"activity:scout:107","kind":"scout","lifecycle":"paused","source_ref":"site/problems/107.json","trust":"recorded"}],"activity_types":["scout"],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[{"commit":"9bdac2f66b17f37fb3267fd296d5635f6b0e209b","repository":"vela_history","source_root":"sha256:9644d68aebfb09708f41c228aaad2f3f0afc810c391048d500d654c749ae3f98"}],"dependency_impact":"problem_local","detail_url":"problems/107.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Pinned authored activity; it does not establish mathematical truth.","inferred":false,"relation":"investigates","source":"activity:scout:107","source_root":"sha256:9644d68aebfb09708f41c228aaad2f3f0afc810c391048d500d654c749a